I would keep it simple: Start a thread to run your method with a gap between executions and wait in the main thread for it to finish.

```
Thread t = new Thread(() -&gt; {
    for (int i = 0, len = ids.length; i &lt; len; i++) {
        myProcessfor20Seconds();
        try {
            if (i &lt; len - 1) // don&#39;t sleep after the last execution
                Thread.sleep(5000);
        } catch (InterruptedException e) {
            throw new RuntimeException(e);
        }
    }
}); // create the Thread with your background code as a Runnable

t.start(); // start the background thread

// Do other stuff while the Thread is running

try {
    t.join(); // wait for thread to finish
} catch (InterruptedException e) {
    throw new RuntimeException(e);
}
```

There are more elegant ways to handle the exceptions, but this is the basics.

