Here&#39;s how to do it using the [stream API](https://www.oracle.com/technical-resources/articles/java/architect-streams-pt2.html).
```java
import java.util.Objects;

public class LowerAndUpperCase {

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String output = &quot;Elmar DidOkLTWdeee&quot;;
        System.out.println(toAlternativeString(output));
    }

    public static String toAlternativeString(String string) {
        Objects.requireNonNull(string);
        StringBuilder sb = string.chars()
                                 .map(c -&gt; Character.isLowerCase((char) c) ? Character.toUpperCase((char) c) : Character.isUpperCase((char) c) ? Character.toLowerCase((char) c) : (char) c)
                                 .collect(() -&gt; new StringBuilder(),
                                          (s, c) -&gt; s.append((char) c),
                                          (s1, s2) -&gt; s1.append(s2));
        return sb.toString();
    }
}
```
- Method [isLowerCase](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/Character.html#isLowerCase(char)) also checks whether its method argument is a letter so no need to call method `isLetter` first.
- Method [chars](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#chars()) returns an `IntStream`, hence the casts to `char`.
- The mapper returns the upper-case of the supplied character &amp;ndash; if it is lower-case &amp;ndash; or the lower-case of the supplied character &amp;ndash; if it is upper-case &amp;ndash; or the character itself if it is neither upper nor lower case.
- In the arguments to the `collect` method, the type of `s` and `s1` and `s2` is `StringBuilder`.

Here is the output when I run the above code.
```none
eLMAR dIDoKltwDEEE
```
Note that the space in the original string is maintained (since the space character is neither upper-case nor lower-case).

